    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clean Needles Victory</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Benjamin Linas letter praises New York State actions that will increase addicts' access to clean needles (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State has taken the first steps toward common-sense H.I.V. and hepatitis prevention. The new budget decriminalizes syringe possession and allows people to buy, without a prescription, sterile needles from a pharmacy (news article, May 6). Finally, we are carrying out lessons learned from the decade-long, multimillion-dollar exploration of the relationship between H.I.V. and injected drugs.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State has taken the first steps toward common-sense H.I.V. and hepatitis prevention. The new budget decriminalizes syringe possession and allows people to buy, without a prescription, sterile needles from a pharmacy (news article, May 6). Finally, we are carrying out lessons learned from the decade-long, multimillion-dollar exploration of the relationship between H.I.V. and injected drugs.</p>
        <p>Increasing access to clean needles decreases the incidence of blood-borne infection without creating new drug use. Needle exchange and pharmacy sales work. That is why every established medical and scientific body to study the issue -- including the National Academy of Sciences, the American Medical Association and the Clinton and Bush AIDS advisory commissions -- concurs on the efficacy of improved access to sterile syringes.</p>
        <p>BENJAMIN LINAS, M.D.  New York, May 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
